[b]tl;dr game has as much polish as an abandoned brick house from the 1600s, it's insane to call this worthy of the title "1.0"[/b]


I'm glad I got this game as a gift, because it's a purchase I would have regretted (and refunded).

Empyrion, at its core, is a survival sandbox game that allows you to freely roam around an entire galaxy and do as you please within it. However, there are a slew of things that make this a much less pleasant experience than it could be - notably:

- Graphics, animations and everything else visual look terrible, even at maximum settings. Models are very low-quality, textures are shoddy at best and body animations are rigid and simple. Furthermore, as far as I can tell, there aren't even moving parts on most equipment, including firearms, and the reloading animation (emphasis on singular "animation") for handheld equipment seems to be recycled across all reloadable equipment (i.e. you'll see the same hand animation for reloading a sidearm, assault rifle and chainsaw);

- Player movement feels both clunky and imprecise - another reviewer stated it well, with the first-person movement feeling like "a camera on wheels" rather than actual walking;

- The AI is brainless, but, at least, is given aimbot when they use ranged weapons. Melee-based enemies, such as arachnids, have so far missed me 100% of the time if I just move backward continuously while firing at them. Ranged ground enemies seem to have exceedingly accurate aim, probably to compensate for the absence of any real strategy in combat other than 'sit still and wait for him to come back into view'. Turrets are also highly accurate, but, given they're computer-operated, that's understandable;

- Low-quality storytelling, sub-par grammar and just disappointingly bad writing style. In particular, the 'campaign' you can embark on from the start is a joke;

- Nutrition system that can inflict numerous debuffs - and zero beneficial buffs - without warning, especially if you ingest ingredients without assembling them into meals. I can understand raw meat causing food poisoning, but things like plant protein (visually shown to be things such as nuts) causing "indigestion" is just irritating;

- Inventory icons that look like shoddy asset store placeholder art;

- Very, very slow progression system that requires substantial grinding (and waiting on long crafting timers) to build anything decent;

- A slew of other, smaller things that further degrade the experience.

I was led to believe this game had more to offer, but I should have figured it was too good to be true at this price. I may still dig deeper into the game to see if there's anything worth living for, but, at the sixteen hour mark, I am very unimpressed.

If you do get this game, it really should be played solely for the large-scale building and exploration experience. In my opinion, the game would literally be better if the story was stripped entirely and more effort was put into the development of visuals, AI, construction, and survival mechanics.

Games that actually do parts of what this game tries to do correctly would include Space Engineers (lacks galactic travel and survival/exploration aspects, but has insanely superior visuals and a much better building system), and No Man's Sky (has galactic travel, quality exploration and superior visuals, but lacks the building system of even Empyrion, let alone Space Engineers).
